1 5 stars? C'mon, be honest, is any Chinese buffet really a 5 star establishment? Alright, let's take an honest look about what you'll get at Buffet @ Asia. . .  First off, ask yourself this question, why do I want to go to an 'all you can eat' Chinese buffet? Certainly price may be an issue (as lunch is under $10), but ultimately, we want to eat A LOT of food, and heck, sometimes we just crave greasy, high fat, higher sodium foods (like say, after a night of heavy drinking, or possibly you've wallowed in intense emotional pain and/or guilt for several years, and you simply feel the need to continue punishing yourself).  Still reading?. . .okay then, the food is like any food you'd expect in an establishment who's number one business is volume. Most of the food sits in a coagulated, goopy mess to hide it's poor quality, because we all know that we're not getting any true nutritional value from the food. But again, we've come to Buffet @ Asia for the cheap price and assortment of high fat/higher sodium foods. . .we're not interested in quality at this time.  My best advice would be to suck it up and spend an extra dollar or two at McDonalds, KFC or Taco Bell and stop kidding yourself that the broccoli in the 'Mystery Chinese Delicacy' is somehow satisfying your daily requirement for vegetables. But, if you're having 'one of those days' (you know who you are), go ahead and indulge. Your body won't approve, but just try to convince yourself that it tastes alright and smile. . .it worked for me today.
